{"actual_usd":0.160525,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":314,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31163,"reply":"\"Yeah, people have tried both of those routes for a long time.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light off the square stones.* \"I don't think they hold the full load.\"\n\n\"Grief visions can explain an experience or two, maybe. They do a worse job with the stubborn public shape of the claim — not just 'I felt him with me,' but 'he was raised,' empty tomb, multiple witnesses, people staking their lives on it, and a movement that doesn't sound like private mourning language.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"And the 'maybe he didn't die' idea always feels thinner to me than people want it to. Roman execution wasn't casual. A half-dead man limping out of a tomb doesn't really generate resurrection faith anyway — it generates 'our teacher barely survived,' which is a different sentence.\"\n\n\"So for me the question isn't 'can I invent a non-supernatural story?' Sure, probably. You can usually invent one.\" *I glance over toward the well chain ticking softly in the square.* \"The question is which account actually fits the thing that happened without shaving off the hardest parts. Christianity is supernatural right at the center or it isn't Christianity in the historic sense — Paul pretty much says as much. If Christ wasn't raised, we're not talking about a slightly revised faith. We're talking about collapse.\"\n\n\"What part feels most live to you — the visions theory, the survival theory, or the general reluctance to let miracle be the answer?\"","rolling_24h_usd":83.56620000000001,"run_id":"eb75967c-2109-4928-a9db-b81b147c3c5b"}
